<TITLE> Shakib needs physiotherapy not surgery </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 8 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh's stand-in captain Shakib Al Hasan will not need surgery on his groin injury but will instead undergo physiotherapy in Australia, says a BCB press release. Shakib arrived in Adelaide for treatment at the end of August and was examined by a physiotherapist, Dr Steve Saunders, and surgeon Dr Peter Malycha. His treatment will last five or six weeks, in which time doctors will assess how the injury is responding, a Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) statement said on Tuesday. He will return to Dhaka for Eid and continue the treatment at home. Shakib said: "I have to continue the therapy for 5-6 weeks and during this time we will be able to assess how the groin is responding to the treatment. For the first couple of weeks I will be working with Dr. Saunders before I return to Dhaka for Eid." He added: "I will continue to treat the injury in accordance with the doctor's instructions at home and I am confident that I will be fit for the series against Zimbabwe. Dr Saunders and Dr Malycha are very optimistic that I will be able to start playing soon." Shakib is the fifth Bangladesh bowler to sustain an injury in recent months after Mashrafe Bin Mortaza, fast bowler Rubel Hossain and Nazmul Hossain and left-arm spinner Abdur Ra
